            "id": "8d8718f941a449c08fda2",
            "questionText": "A maglev train is 150 m long and operates with a current of 1000 A flowing through coils uniformly distributed along its length. These coils interact with a perpendicular magnetic field of 5 T generated by the guideway. Determine the force per meter experienced by the train due to this interaction.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "391a5ff160164f79a4636",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the correct formula for the magnetic force acting on a current-carrying conductor. Which of the following formulas correctly represents the force when a conductor of length $!$L$!$ carrying a current $!$I$!$ is placed perpendicular to a magnetic field $!$B$!$?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "f811e506-c07a-4cc9-8b32-e4a587510caf"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$F = I L B \\sin \\theta$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$F = q v B \\sin \\theta$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$F = I \\cdot B$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "80232c46ab224ddca90fc",
                    "stepText": "Great, now that you have considered the magnetic force, let's determine how to express the force per unit length for the train. Since the coils are uniformly distributed along the train, the total force is evenly divided by its length. Which of the following expressions correctly gives the force per meter?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "f811e506-c07a-4cc9-8b32-e4a587510caf"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$f = I B$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$f = I L B$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$f = \\frac{I B}{L}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "4c9d295803bd4c20bac68",
                    "stepText": "Finally, using the expression you identified, substitute the given values $!$I = 1000$!$ A and $!$B = 5$!$ T to compute the numerical value of the force per meter experienced by the train.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "5000"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "N/m",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "f811e506-c07a-4cc9-8b32-e4a587510caf"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
        },
        {
            "id": "cc69d80b94dd4d7f91e48",
            "questionText": "In a mass spectrometer, singly ionized carbon atoms (charge $!$+1.60\\times10^{-19}$!$ C) are accelerated through a 500 V potential difference and then enter a 0.8 T uniform magnetic field, oriented perpendicularly to their velocity. Assuming the mass of a carbon ion is 12 amu (with $!$1\\,amu = 1.66\\times10^{-27}$!$ kg), determine the radius of the circular path the carbon ions will follow in the magnetic field.",
            "imageText": "",
            "steps": [
                {
                    "id": "072b7bed8efe49679063a",
                    "stepText": "Let's start by identifying the correct expression that calculates the kinetic energy gained by a charged particle when it is accelerated through a potential difference $!$V$!$. Which of the following formulas represents this relationship?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "2ea34cb0-b608-4374-9d6c-63725f3e0956",
                        "306b3cf8-0e61-4b6b-b694-4907440c3f02"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$K.E. = qV$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$K.E. = \\frac{V}{q}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$K.E. = \\frac{q}{V}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "4f7468a97b4240a4ad874",
                    "stepText": "Great! Now, using the given value of 12 amu for the carbon ion and the conversion $!$1\\,amu = 1.66\\times10^{-27}$!$ kg, calculate the mass of the carbon ion. Multiply these values to obtain the mass.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "1.99e-26"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "kg",
                    "stepConcepts": [],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "2c9b11e7ae42456a8a031",
                    "stepText": "Now that you have the ion's kinetic energy from the potential difference, identify the correct expression to compute the velocity of the ion using the energy relation $!$\\frac{1}{2}mv^2 = qV$!$. Which of the following expressions should be used?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "e5888dcb-4bc0-4c40-8775-34a2ee76ab02"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v = \\sqrt{\\frac{2qV}{m}}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v = \\frac{qV}{m}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$v = \\sqrt{\\frac{qV}{m}}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "f36cd82a07c742be883ea",
                    "stepText": "Using the energy relation $!$\\frac{1}{2}mv^2 = qV$!$ with the computed kinetic energy and the mass you calculated, determine the velocity of the carbon ion. Enter the numerical value.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "8.97e4"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m/s",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "e5888dcb-4bc0-4c40-8775-34a2ee76ab02"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                },
                {
                    "id": "b8e7cbe23be34cc4933d2",
                    "stepText": "Next, when the ion enters a magnetic field perpendicularly, the magnetic force acts as the centripetal force. Identify the correct expression that relates the radius of the ion's circular path to its mass, velocity, charge, and the magnetic field. Which formula best represents this relation?",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        ""
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "522866e5-3c70-4a23-87f0-6b202495073f"
                    ],
                    "options": [
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$r = \\frac{mv}{qB}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": true
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$r = \\frac{qB}{mv}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        },
                        {
                            "optionText": "$!$r = \\frac{mv^2}{qB}$!$",
                            "optionImage": "",
                            "isCorrect": false
                        }
                    ]
                },
                {
                    "id": "af5137cdd55544f7a537c",
                    "stepText": "Finally, using the expression for the radius and the provided values ($!$m = 1.99\\times10^{-26}$!$ kg, $!$q = 1.60\\times10^{-19}$!$ C, $!$v = 8.97\\times10^{4}$!$ m/s, and $!$B = 0.8$!$ T), calculate the radius of the carbon ion's circular path. Provide the numerical value.",
                    "stepText2": "",
                    "stepImage": "",
                    "stepSolveAnswer": [
                        "0.0140"
                    ],
                    "stepSolveAnswerUnits": "m",
                    "stepConcepts": [
                        "522866e5-3c70-4a23-87f0-6b202495073f"
                    ],
                    "options": []
                }
            ]
        }
    ]
